## Known architectural risk — flagged, not resolved, investigate before relying on it

The Confluence doc's §5.1 specifies the Context Keeper as **"User-invocable: false"** —
meaning it should be triggered automatically by other agents, not picked by a human
from a menu. But custom Agents in GitHub Copilot (the mechanism we're using for it,
per the decision above) are, as far as I've confirmed, **user-selected personas** —
something a person manually switches into via the agent picker. I have not found a
documented mechanism for one agent to silently call another and get a value back while
staying in control of the conversation.

The one related mechanism I'm aware of is a `handoffs:` frontmatter field that lets one
agent switch context to another — but that hands control over, it doesn't return an
answer to the caller. Before assuming this works for an automated pipeline, check
whether `handoffs` (or anything else available in this Copilot environment) actually
supports a call-and-return pattern. If it doesn't, tell me explicitly that this is a
real limitation rather than building around it silently — this affects whether the
whole "Master Orchestrator calls the Context Keeper automatically" premise is even
achievable with this mechanism today, versus something that still requires a human to
manually switch agents at each lookup point.

